Oriented Object Programming comes with a lot of concepts that you need to know in order to not breakdown in front of errors. 
There are two concepts here that can help you deal with these errors :
- **Visibility** (of variables and methods): The default visibility of your variables is *public*, which is not often a good idea when dealing with class fields. With the right visibility, you will get more specific errors. 
- **Static** (variables and methods) : 
They are variables and methods that belong to a class rather than instances of the class.
Here is an example :
Let&#39;s say you have a class A:

    public class A{

      static int i = 0;
      int j ;

      public A(int k){
        this.i = k;
      }
      public static printI(){
        System.out.println(this.i);
      }
      public printJ(){
        System.out.println(this.j);
      }
}


Then :

    A a = new A();
    A b = new B();
    
    a.printI() # 0
    
    a.i++; 
    a.j++;
    a.printI() # 1
    A.printI() #1
    a.printJ(); # 1
    b.printJ(); # 0

As you can see, i is shared by a and b.

**And even A**, the class itself. That means that you don&#39;t need the instantiate an object of A in order to manipulate i. 
It&#39;s the same thing like when you do Math.PI (PI is a static variable of Math class).
So if you get this, you can also understand that a **static method can&#39;t manipulate non-static variables** (because a non-static variable is born at instantiation of an object of the class while a static variable doesn&#39;t need that).

In your case, main is (generally) a static method, that&#39;s why it asks you to change variables to static.

There are many basic notions like those in order to code in Java. [Here][1] is a good lite java tutorial.


  [1]: https://www.w3schools.com/java/default.asp

