You define two different `SecurityFilterChain` beans: one with `Basic` auth and the other one with `oauth2client()` and `oauth2Login()`.

This two security filter-chains must be decorated with `@Order` to determine which is tried first.

The one tried first must have a `securityMatcher` to define which requests it applies to. In your case, a matcher on the `Authorization` header starting with `Basic ` seems a good candidate.

```java
@Bean
@Order(Ordered.LOWEST_PRECEDENCE - 1)
SecurityFilterChain basicAuthFilterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {

	// process only requests with HTTP Basic Authorization
	http.securityMatcher((HttpServletRequest request) -&gt; {
		return Optional.ofNullable(request.getHeader(HttpHeaders.AUTHORIZATION)).map(h -&gt; {
			return h.toLowerCase().startsWith(&quot;basic &quot;);
		}).orElse(false);
	});

	http.httpBasic(withDefaults());

	...

	return http.build();
}

@Bean
@Order(Ordered.LOWEST_PRECEDENCE)
SecurityFilterChain oauth2ClientFilterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
	http.oauth2Client(withDefaults());
	http.oauth2Login(withDefaults());
	http.authorizeHttpRequests(ex -&gt; ex
		// This is required for OAuth2 login (used during authoriztion_code flow, so BEFORE the user is authenticated)
		.requestMatchers(Stream.of(&quot;/login/**&quot;, &quot;/oauth2/**&quot;).map(AntPathRequestMatcher::new).toArray(RequestMatcher[]::new)).permitAll()
		.anyRequest().authenticated());

	...

	return http.build();
}
```

